<TABLE BORDER=0 cellpadding=4 border=0 cellspacing=1 WIDTH="95%"><TR bgcolor="#000000"><TD COLSPAN=2><CENTER><FONT SIZE="2" COLOR="#00ff00" FACE="Verdana, Arial">T O P I C  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R E V I E W</font></CENTER></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Banedon</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I have 2 Pcs, 1 running windoze and 1 running Linux. Currently the windoze pc has a NIC which is connected to my cable modem. I read that SEQ only works with a Hub. Therefore i am getting a hub but i would like to know whether i must necessary make the Linux box the router. Can i just plug the Cable Modem into the hub along with the other 2 PCs? Will this work? Some friends said no and i need to install 2 NICs in my linux box and use it as a router but i do not want to switch on my Linux Box everytime i wanna surf the net. Any advice?</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">V1olator</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Two solutions:<P>Setup the Linux box with 2 NICs and get NAT up and running on it.<P>Buy a broadband router (Linksys and others make them).  Plug the modem into it, and hook a hub (router has switched ports, no good here) into the router.  Hook the systems into the hub.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">freeza</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">linksys makes a good router (befsr11) but make sure not to use a linksys 10/100 hub, they dont broadcast packets.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Mr Ripley</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Oh the way I do it is have a HUB plug in my DSL modem and my 2 pcs into it. Then have my win box connect to the DSL and then run sygate and share it with my linux box. Is that why showeq is not working right? Well neway if u do it my way u gotta use a crossover cable to connect ur dsl/cable modem to ur hub i believe. oh well<BR>mr ripley<BR></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Step</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">The way i have mine setup is with a Netgear 4 port HUB with Cable Modem connected to the UPLINK port and Linux Box and Windows Box each connected to normal ports on the HUB. Works great. Each computer gets their own IP from the isps server thingy.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">raazer</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">You can get the Netgear RT311, It works like a charm. I run it and a hub attached to it where my linux box and my windows box both pull off of while running NAT.  the RT311 will set up NAT, and a firewall for you all in the same instance.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Diesel</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Your setups are all fine and dandy but what about security? You do realize that your boxes are bare naked on the internet. All you need is another NIC in that Linux box and BANG! you have a firewall....throw up some ipchains and your safe and sound. Ok so its a little more detailed than that but I'm sure you guys can RTFM.<P>Just some friendly advice from a Security Engineer!<P>Diesel	</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">k7</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">fyi:  The linux befsr series or routers has one that is just the router without the switch.  It has all the features of the 4 and 8 port variants, but without the switch you're forced to use a hub, which is what you're supposed to do for seq anyway.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Step</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Dun mind about security. All networking services are off =]</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">freeza</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">k7: this is the befsr11 i spoke of earlier.  i'm running it and it works great.  has lots of nifty features.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">WhiteFire</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I would have to agree with Diesel about setting the linux box up as the firewall.  That is going to be the cheapest and the most secure way to do it.  I will go over quickly what hardware you will need and what you are going to have to do to setup it up.<P>#1 You will need 2 NIC cards in your Linux Box.  It can be done with one, but when you Alais one NIC like that you defeat the whole point of setting up the firewall.  It does not have to be a great NIC either, just one that works.  I use a SMC brand NIC in my Linux box at home and I get them for about 7.00 each at the store.<P>#2 Next you will need to network the Win95/98/ME/NT computer to the Linux Box.  This can be done with either a eathernet hub or a Crossover Cable.  If you are only going to have the linux box and one Windows computer then the Crossover cable will work fine.  If you get another computer later and decide that you want to put it on your network at home then you can buy a small hub at that time, but for just networking 2 computers togather I would use the Crossover Cabel (approx. $5.00 US Dollars).<P>Now I have a Linux Firewall setup and running at home, but I run Redhat Linux.  If you are going to do this with any other version of Linux the commands might vary.<P>First Install both NIC cards into the linux box.  Assign one NIC card the IP address give to you from your ISP and give the other NIC and IP address that you make up.  Lets use 192.168.0.1 for example.  Plug your cable modem into the NIC card that has the corrosponding IP address from your ISP and plug the Crossover cable from the other NIC card in the Linux Box to the NIC card in the Windows Box.<P>Now you have to enable packet forwarding on the Linux Box.  This can be done once you are logged in as root by typing:<BR>#echo 1 &gt; /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forwarding<P>After you have enabled packet forwarding you need to setup the ipchains rule to allow the windows machine access to the Internet.  Again make sure you are logged in as root and type:<BR>#ipchains -I forward -s 192.168.0.0/24 -d 0/0 -j MASQ<BR>This command will allow all computers on your network with a 192.168.0.X IP address full access to the internet through the Linux Box.<P>After setting up the ipchains rule your Linux Box should be configured correctly.  The only thing that is left is to configure the windows machine.  This is very easy once the Linux Box is setup.  Go into your network properities and select your NIC card.  Give your Windows machine an IP address on the made up network for example 192.168.0.2 with a subnet mask of 255.255.255.0.  Next you will have to configure a Gateway.  In this feild you will give it the IP address of the Linux Box 192.168.0.1.  Lastley you will need to give it a DNS server.  That information will be provided by your ISP.  Just enter the IP address that they give you in the DNS search order box and you are done.  Reboot and Windows box you should should be able to get on the Internet.<P>One last suggestion I would make to anyone that is going to setup a Linux Firewall.  I would install and confiure TCP Wrappers.  The best way to do this is in the /etc/hosts.deny file add the line ALL:ALL This will deny access to anyone that may attempt to access services that your Linux box is running over the Internet such as Telnet, or FTP.<P>I hope this helps and if you have any further questions feel free to post them.<P>Whitefire</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
</FONT>
